  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the largest cities in the world by area?",
  "response": "Measuring the largest cities in the world by area can be somewhat complicated, as definitions of city boundaries and the methodology for calculating area can vary significantly. However, here are some of the cities often cited as the largest by area, considering their administrative boundaries:\n\n1. **New York City, USA**: The city is known for its extensive metropolitan area, exceeding 468.9 square miles (1,213 km\u00b2). \n\n2. **Tokyo, Japan**: Greater Tokyo, which includes the core city and surrounding municipalities, spans approximately 8,547 square kilometers (3,300 square miles).\n\n3. **Chicago, USA**: The metropolitan area covers around 10,874 square kilometers (4,200 square miles).\n\n4. **Atlanta, USA**: While the city itself is smaller, the metropolitan area covers about 21,694 square kilometers (8,376 square miles).\n\n5. **Houston, USA**: The city and surrounding metropolitan area cover approximately 26,061 square kilometers (10,069 square miles).\n\n6. **Dallas-Fort Worth, USA**: The metro area covers around 9,286 square miles (24,093 square kilometers).\n\n7. **Los Angeles, USA**: The Greater Los Angeles area encompasses over 4,850 square miles (12,561 square kilometers).\n\n8. **Beijing, China**: The municipality of Beijing covers approximately 16,410.54 square kilometers (6,336 square miles).\n\n9. **Shanghai, China**: Shanghai's administrative area covers around 6,340.5 square kilometers (2,448.1 square miles).\n\n10. **Brasilia, Brazil**: Covering around 5,802 square kilometers (2,240 square miles).\n\nThese figures often include metropolitan and administrative regions rather than just the core city, which can lead to variation in reported size. Note that as urban areas grow and merge over time, these numbers may shift.",
